title: [DS] FCoE multi-hop performance degraded because of QoS config mismatch [Fabric Interconnect A]
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
Customer reported degraded performance when moving from native Fibre Channel to FCOE Multi-Hop.
CONDITIONS:
UCS <--> Nexus 5K using FCOE Multi-Hop.
UCS QOS configured with 2 no-drop classes.
N5k QOS configured with 1 no-drop class.
MITIGATION:
If using 2 drop classes in UCSM and 1 drop class on N5K, then match QOS setting by checking "Packet Drop" selection on mismatch priority class.

Further Problem Description:
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Note: DSIG Confidence Level: 99% - please review bug and verify impact
The number of no-drop QoS classes should be the same on the FI's and the upstream network devices for PFC to negotiate properly.

title: [DS] FCoE multi-hop performance degraded because of QoS config mismatch [Fabric Interconnect B]
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
Customer reported degraded performance when moving from native Fibre Channel to FCOE Multi-Hop.
CONDITIONS:
UCS <--> Nexus 5K using FCOE Multi-Hop.
UCS QOS configured with 2 no-drop classes.
N5k QOS configured with 1 no-drop class.
MITIGATION:
If using 2 drop classes in UCSM and 1 drop class on N5K, then match QOS setting by checking "Packet Drop" selection on mismatch priority class.

Further Problem Description:
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Note: DSIG Confidence Level: 99% - please review bug and verify impact
The number of no-drop QoS classes should be the same on the FI's and the upstream network devices for PFC to negotiate properly.

title: [DS] FI sends SmartCallHome messages in wrong format
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
UCS 6248, 6296 and 6332 Series Fabric Interconnects that send call home inventory messages to Cisco's Smart Call Home does not get processed due to incorrect XML format which prevents new devices from getting registered and processed. Reports also may not appear as expected.
CONDITIONS:
XML need to be in expected format, all the tags should be in readable format.
MITIGATION:
SCH support team is able to manually edit the XML and reprocess the message and then work with SCH development to complete the device registrations. XML can be tweaked and processed back to SCH.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Though there is work around, it has to be correct on the device live call home data to avoid the same issue.
This DS is not checking for models because the code commits were made at a firmware level and were not model specific.

title:
[DS] Adobe Flash End of support  
 [Fabric Interconnect A]
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
The WebUI of all UCS Manager releases for release trains earlier than 3.1(3a), which includes the 2.2(x) release train, are Java-based and might not be accessible on browser versions that will deprecate support for Flash.
If running an impacted version and a browser without flash, the administrator will be unable to open the UCSM GUI.
CONDITIONS:
See "Products Affected" section of field notice.
MITIGATION:
Cisco has migrated from Flash to HTML5 for the UCS Manager GUI. While Cisco will continue to provide applicable service and support such as critical security fixes via patch releases through the end-of-support dates (https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/servers-unified-computing/ucs-manager/eos-eol-notice-listing.html) for the impacted releases, Cisco does not plan to retrofit those releases with an HTML5-based WebUI.

Customers who might be impacted by this deprecation should consider these alternatives:

Upgrade to a UCS Manager release on the 3.1(3) or 3.2 trains, or to a later release that supports an HTML5-based GUI interface.
Use the CLI or XML API interface to control and configure the servers attached to the Fabric Interconnects.
Access vKVM through the XML API in case the WebUI is not available.
A later and recommended version of software can be downloaded from the Software Download page (login required).
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Note: DSIG Confidence Level: 75% - please review bug and verify impact
CSCvw71242

title: TRANSCEIVER DETAILS FOR SFPs IN IOMs, FABRIC INTERCONNECTS and STANDALONE FEXs: SNs, PIDS/DESCRIPTIONs, LOCATIONs - IF NON-CISCO Transceiver Models, they are NOT Supported: Inform Customer of Risk - Submit Sales Lead for all NON-CISCO transeivers! - DO NOT RMA
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
NON-Cisco branded SFPs/Transceivers may cause low eye height, unexplained CRC errors, network performance complaints and the customer is leaving their environment vulnerable to networking issues, described here, when using unsupported transceivers. The 'Vendor' name must begin with 'CISCO-' and then the manufacturers name. This ensures us they have purchased tested and qualified transceivers to operate with our gear and live up to the performance we promise our customers
CONDITIONS:
Currently this module is set to provide TAC Awareness about NON-CISCO transceivers being unsupported and to generate sales leads when confirming NON-CISCO branded SFPs in a customer's environment. Also it can be handy to have all of the SFP PIDS, Vendors, SNs, including the IOM's and FEX's SFPs details. So set to severity 'NOTICE' I will change the condition in due time to:

Identified a non-Cisco SFP in sam_techsupport under `show chassis inventory expand` at the 'Xcvr Vendor:' line or in sw_techsupport `show transceiver details` at the 'name is' line
MITIGATION:
Determine if the non-Cisco transceivers are causing a networking issue you may be investigating now.
Inform the customer of the risk their environment is in while running non-Cisco and unsupported Transceivers.
Submit a Sales Lead and inform the account team you have found a batch of non-Cisco Transceivers and there may be even more throughout their network!
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
There are companies that manufacture Transceivers and will slap a Cisco Product ID on it and then sell them to suppliers who then sell these, essentially counterfeit, transceivers to our customers at a much lower price.

Justification for these transceivers being explicitly not supported can be found in SR 681819092 where the customer added new Chassis using non-Cisco SFPs. A dozen interfaces all incrementing NON STOMP CRC errors, coming up with an eye height in the 50 mv, or less, range with transceiver vendor name 'OEM'. While the 'type' showed a legitimate Cisco PID. This was the part that threw us off, but discussed with the Business Unit and determined the SFPs were not supported and they had to purchase Cisco branded SFPs and the issue went away immediately.
Note: There are times non-Cisco SFPs are supported, for instance, if a rack server is using a Qlogic, Emulex, or Intel card and they have SFPs that are supported by those adapters. These scenarios will not be flagged by this module and did want to share that there can be extenuating cicumstances.


Please see Section 6 of Cisco's Public Non-Entitlement Policy: 'THIRD PARTY COMPONENTS' stating, 'Cisco also reserves the right to charge the customer per then current time and material rates for services provided to the customer when Cisco determines, after having provided such services, that the root cause of the defective product was caused by a third-party vendor supplied product.'

https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/warranties/warranty-doc-c99-740959.html#_Toc3320258
EVIDENCE:
sam_techsupport under `show chassis inventory expand` at the 'Xcvr Vendor:' line or in sw_techsupport `show transceiver details` at the 'name is' line

title: [BTF] Customer is not experiencing latest bug fixes and features
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
The customer is not covered by the most recent bug fixes, nor do they have the most recent features available.
CONDITIONS:
Customer's not running BU reccomended infrastructure code. BU Recommended code is designated by a 'star' next to the release on software center
MITIGATION:
1. Review any golden rules on case
2. Re-Confirm that customer has no incompatible hardware for going to the latest recommended version of code.
3. Communicate to the customer they are not on BU recommended versions of code and may want to consider upgrading to have access to latest bug fixes and features.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Upgrade to UCS Manager 2.2(8) from 2.2(7) or earlier
  • UCS Manager 2.2(8) is the patch point for the UCS Manager 2.2 code train - i.e. the only place we are providing patches. The latest security fixes, including Spectre Variant #2, are included in UCS Manager 2.2(8j).
  • On Next Reboot - a highly requested feature to allow scheduled or user acknowledgement changes to happen automatically when there is an externally-initiated operating system/hypervisor reboot.
  • Graceful shutdown options.
  • ...and more!

Upgrade to UCS Manager 3.1(x) - especially 3.1(3) - from UCS Manager 2.2(x)
  • HTML 5 user interface.
  • HTML 5 KVM client.
  • New hardware including 6332 Fabric Interconnect Series, S3260 Storage servers, Secure Encrypted Drives, and numerous peripherals.
  • UCS Manager 3.1(3) is the patch point for the UCS Manager 3.1 code train.
  • ...and more!

Upgrade to UCS Manager 3.2(x) - especially 3.2(3p) - from UCS Manager 2.2(x) or 3.1(x)
  • Support for UCS and Hyperflex M5 generation servers and numerous additional peripherals.
  • Support for Cisco Intersight through the Device Connector.
  • Prepare for update stages firmware while the systems are online without a maintenance window. Activating the firmware, which may require a reboot, is done much more quickly reducing the downtime during the maintenance window.
  • UCS Manager 3.2(3) is the patch point for the UCS Manager 3.2 code train.
  • ...and more!

TAC-BU Agreement on software recommendations
UCS Upgrade Guides
BU Suggested Releases
EVIDENCE:
sam_techsupportinfo: show system firmware

title: Duplicate zone entries created on UCS fabric
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
Duplicate zone sets with the exact same initiator and target are created when doing local zoning on the UCS FI
CONDITIONS:
This was seen in FC switch mode on 2.2(2c) code when using local zoning. This happens when we use the same combination of initiator and target-wwpn in both storage-connectivity-policy and boot-policy.
MITIGATION:
Remove the initiator/target-wwpn from either the storage-connectivity-policy or the boot-policy.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
CSCuy58242
EVIDENCE:
sw_techsupportinfo: show zoneset vsan 1-4093

external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
Newly created vLAN ID in vNIC template is displayed as 1 for vNICs under service profiles after deleting their their parent SP templates.
CONDITIONS:
This happens only when the SP is being derived from its initial/updating template and the parent template is deleted.
MITIGATION:
Unbind the vNIC from its template and bind it back.
Or unbind the service profile from the service profile template.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
CSCvb57270
EVIDENCE:

title: UCSM QoS configuration issue: shallow buffers lead to tail drop
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
UCSM QoS configuration issue: shallow buffers lead to tail drop
CONDITIONS:
QoS misconfiguration
MITIGATION:
See additional_info
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Teammates wanted this info on manual runs.
Storage traffic (NFS/iSCSI/vMotion) is very bursty and performs poorly with shallow buffers. Buffers(q-size) is typically 20-29kB for Platinum/Gold/Silver/Bronze. Using 9000MTU allows 2-3 packets to fit into the buffers before discarding(tail drop). One of Platinum/Gold/Silver/Bronze can be set to no-drop which increases buffers allowing about 9 packets. Platinum or Gold may be a cool name, but is horrible for bursty traffic. Gold is used by NetApp for all IP storage traffic(NFS/iSCSI/CIFS) and cannot be changed on the NetApp(See: NetApp KB 3013708).

    (shallow) = q-size / MTU < 4
    (discards) = Pkts discarded on ingress > 100
    (unused) = 0 RX and 0 TX
    (asymmetric) = 0 RX ## TX or ## RX or 0 TX
    (no-drop) = larger q-size because 'Packet Drop' is unchecked
    (jumbo) = 9000MTU configured
As a troubleshooting step move NFS/iSCSI/vMotion traffic into Best Effort which has very large buffers.

Unused Platinum/Gold/Silver/Bronze waste precious buffers, disable unused QoS classes to return buffers to Best Effort.

Asymmetric traffic is usually due to QoS configuration being disjoint or inconsistant, marking packets in one direction/endpoint but not the other direction/endpoint.

Asymmetric traffic and Jumbo when Best Effort also is NOT Jumbo can cause large return packets to be fragmented or stomped(mtu_vio) degrading performance.

Note: rx and tx numbers are 32-bit unsigned integers which resets after 4294967296. This can skew the discard percent if FIs have been up for a long time.
http://bug.cisco.com/CSCuh72875
https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/datacenter/nexus5000/sw/qos/521_n1_1/b_5k_QoS_Config_521N11/b_5k_QoS_Config_521N11_chapter_01001.html

title: LDAP domain name character limitation
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
Could get authentication failures when attempting to login.
CONDITIONS:
Since the username is added to the domain name a domain name of over 20 characters could be problematic.
MITIGATION:
Check that the domain name and username together are below 27 characters.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Check the link (under 'Creating an Authentication Domain') for full details on character limitations with domain names/user names.
http://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/unified_computing/ucs/sw/gui/config/guide/2-2/b_UCSM_GUI_Configuration_Guide_2_2/configuring_authentication.html#task_8315FBC7CBAB40EAAB1A9C14AA0093CE
EVIDENCE:
sam_techsupportinfo: show fault detail

title: FI Traffic Balance Analysis
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
Customers with an unbalanced amount of traffic open themselves to seeing congestion sooner rather than later
CONDITIONS:
This module always shows for CSE analysis
MITIGATION:
Review the stats shown below, determine if there is a big enough difference to suggest to the CU to make any changes. If a CU is using vNICs with Enable Failover checked, they may want to migrate some of the vNICs from one fabric to the other. If the CU is using Active / Passive load balancing at the OS level, they may wish to migrate between the fabrics to more evenly share load.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Several counters are provided to help the CSE make a better analysis since some counters may roll or be reset in certain circumstances
todo
EVIDENCE:
sw_techsupportinfo on both FI's using interface counters from show interface, show queuing interface and show hardware internal carmel all-ports detail

title: UCS FI switchport interface errors
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
Traffic may be corrupted causing network connectivity issues.
CONDITIONS:
Interface counters contain non-zero 'input error' or fc interfaces contain non-zero 'discards'.
MITIGATION:
1) Determine if errors/discards are incrementing.
2) Check hardware counters(`show hardware internal carmel crc` and `show hardware internal carmel eye`) detailed in TZs (on both sides of the wire); and check for MTU mismatches.
3) Isolate cause of errors: shut/no shut ports, reseat twinax/SFP/fiber, clean/cletop fiber, change cable/SFP/switchport/NIC/etc see if errors follow cable/SFP/switchport/NIC/etc.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Interface errors may be caused by MTU violations and/or CRC(NOT_STOMP) frames.
If CRC(NOT_STOMP) increments and switchport is in a port-channel and also using twinax; check TZ1 for bugs: UCS CSCuo76425 CSCuw36398 / Nexus 5000 CSCuj86736
https://techzone.cisco.com/t5/BDB-App-Store-Scripts/BORG-Creating-python-parser-modules-that-detect-problems-in/ta-p/711491#anc14
https://techzone.cisco.com/t5/Nexus-5000-2000/Nexus-5000-Input-Errors-CRCs-on-port-channel-connected-via/ta-p/663072
https://techzone.cisco.com/t5/B-Series/Intermittent-Connectivity-on-UCS-N5k-Troubleshooting-Stomps-and/ta-p/540147
https://techzone.cisco.com/t5/B-Series/Intermittent-Connectivity-on-UCS-N5k-Troubleshooting-Stomps-and/ta-p/540145
https://techzone.cisco.com/t5/B-Series/FlexPod-Common-Performance-Problems/ta-p/686817
CSCuz92545
EVIDENCE:
sw_techsupportinfo: `show interface` `show hardware internal carmel counters interrupt` `show hardware internal carmel all-ports detail`

title: FC MAC statistics analyzer for UCS NXOS
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
Customer may experience variety of problems - performance or perceived instability.
CONDITIONS:
This module looks into UCS switch tech support and analyzes FC-MAC ASIC counters and interrupts.
MITIGATION:
Monitor designated interfaces either via `show interface fcX/Y` or `show hardware internal fc-mac X port y interrupt-counts` or `show hardware internal fc-mac X port Y statistics`
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
Some errors may be expected, especially in an environment, which has been up for a while
This script is meant to aide in troubleshooting, not substitute it.
The logic is simple, look for frequent interrupts and known drops/discard/garbage counters in switch tech supports
http://wwwin-eng.cisco.com/Eng/SAVBU/Projects/Oregon/QA/Before-Avalon/Debugging/Master_Debug.doc
EVIDENCE:
UCS SW tech support on FI A and B, under `show hardware internal fc-mac all-ports`

Interrupt Count = (Completion Queues + 2) rounded up to nearest power of 2

Cisco usNIC Deployment Guide for Cisco UCS B-Series Blade Servers

title: [BTF] UCS Fabric Interconnect clock / NTP configuration
external_text:
SYMPTOMS:
    UCS FI clocks NOT in sync can cause issues including failed upgrades.
CONDITIONS:
    Always, date math using `show clock` output often breaks in python.
MITIGATION:
Verify FI clocks are close(with in a few minutes). If FI clocks are out of sync, is NTP configured? If NTP server NOT configured suggest customer configure NTP. UCSM / Admin / Time Zone Management / Add NTP Server / [Customer NTP Server] / [OK] / [Save Changes] If NTP is configured, but clocks are off: Suggest customer verify reachablity/firewalls from UCS FI to NTP servers. Check `show ntp peer-status` Delete NTP servers and readd NTP servers to force a re-sync.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:
    Cautions, Guidelines, and Limitations for Upgrading with Auto Install
    Time, Date, and Time Zone on Fabric Interconnects Must Be Identical
    To ensure that the fabric interconnects in a cluster configuration are in sync, you must ensure that they are configured for the same date, time, and time zone. We recommend that you configure an NTP server and the correct time zone in both fabric interconnects. If the date, time or time zone in the fabric interconnects are out of sync, the Auto Install might fail.

https://scripts.cisco.com/app/bmc_sensor_info/
EVIDENCE:
`show clock`
